https://linktr.ee/GridSquares

Continuing the conversation----
One thing I wanted to address. I've seen in the comment section some discussion happening about the Chinese companies, internet data, and the acquisition of that data. 

 I was in all source intelligence analysts in the US Army. What are my specific tasks was to Target. Meaning, it was my job to find, fixate, and know everything about a particular person's place or thing using every tool available at my disposal. Including public social media accounts.
That being said, Tiktok is no more a threat than facebook, Twitter, or really any other social media platforms. The United States based companies are guilty of selling our data to the very same bad actors that we accuse tiktok of working with. 

And yes, the United States government can look in on you. Typically they have to have a reason, essentially will need something like a warrant most times. However, in the past it has been reported that certain agencies have collected on the United States citizens without probable cause etc.

This does not mean that there are many other reasons why tiktok is a bit of a problem. One reason why politicians of every ilk in the United States want to get rid of it. Is that it has become kind of a watering hole, somewhere for people to collect and communicate. Sure there's silly dances, stupid challenges on some parts of the app. However, there's a lot of community and political discussion to be found. I'm proud to say I was able to get a few thousand people to sign up to vote, for example. 

